Introduction

A Risk Management Program has been implemented at ATOFINA Chemicals Inc.'s  Riverview Plant for the reduction of accidental releases of hazardous materials.  This Risk Management Plan (RMP) summarizes the management, administrative, procedural, and engineering controls that work together  to minimize the risk to the facility community from hazardous chemical releases.  The Plan summary is organized to correspond with specific Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) RMP definitions and requirements, including:

C Introduction;
C ATOFINA Chemicals' policies to protect health, environment, and safety;
C Hazard Assessment;
C Prevention Program;
C Five-Year Accident History;
C Emergency Response Plan; 
C Planned changes to improve safety; and
C Clean Air Act Amendments Title V Permit Status.


ATOFINA Chemicals' Policies for Health, Environment, and Safety

Risk management and safety have been important concerns at ATOFINA Chemicals for many years; this RMP formalizes and documents these activities.  ATOFINA Chemicals is committed to conducting its operations in a safe, responsible manner and to reducing risks to health and the environment.

This commitment to health, environment, and safety (HES) starts with the Chief Executive Officer (CEO). Senior management routinely dedicates time to a review of HES matters, including safety.  This emphasis on safety is carried through to the facility level, where the management team and the Joint Health, Environmental and Safety Committee regularly review safety performance, implement enhancements, and strive for continuous improvement.  The success of ATOFINA Chemicals= HES programs is also reflected by a strong commitment to safety by employees and contractors.

ATOFINA Chemicals= HES programs include policies, procedures, standards, and guidance materials designed to fulfill ATOFINA Chemicals= commitment to health, environment, and safety.  These materials include Risk Management Program guidance to help our faciliti

ls has an array of mitigation measures to reduce any potential impacts.  Examples of mitigation measures that would lessen the impacts of the Alternative Release Scenarios are listed below.

C Chemical specific leak detectors in certain areas of the facility, including certain railcar unloading stations to provide early warning of a potential release;

C Flammable gas leak detectors in many areas of the facility to provide early warning of a potential release;

C Certain loading operations and vessels are equipped with high level alarms to alert personnel and to reduce the potential for overfills;

C Loading and unloading operations are under continuous observation by operators to detect any problems and to quickly respond;

C Certain railcars containing flammable gasses and toxic liquids/gases are equipped with remote operated valves or valve actuators which can shut off the flow of material in the event of a pipeline or unloading hose rupture;

C Many storage tanks are diked to contain a potential release and allow the release to be covered with water or neutralizing materials to reduce the release of vapors;

C Many areas of the facility are equipped with sprinkler systems for fire protection, including dedicated deluge systems for railcar systems for flammable and toxic gases.  Activation of these sprinkler systems also reduces the release of vapors;

C There are fire alarm stations and fire extinguishers located throughout the facility.  Fire alarm tests are done twice per week.  Employees are routinely trained in the use of fire extinguishers; 

C There is an on-site facility Emergency Response Team on duty 24 hours per day, 365 days  per year.  The team receives over 40 hours of training per year including response to and mitigation of releases and fires.  The team also performs frequent emergency response drills to ensure a rapid, well coordinated and effective response; and

C The facility maintains an on-going dialogue with the LEPC to provide for a prompt

 coordination response in the event of an unforeseen incident.

General Accidental Release Prevention Program

ATOFINA Chemicals has a prevention program in place to minimize the risk of hazardous chemical releases in accordance with the Occupational Health and Safety Administration (OSHA) Process Safety Management (PSM) standard (29 CFR 1910. 119) and the EPA Risk Management Program.  This prevention program covers those processes that handle covered chemicals above the threshold quantity of either the PSM or RMP rules.

The prevention program provides a structured approach to preventing accidents.  Some of the specific activities in the prevention program include:

C In-depth process hazard analyses are completed at least every five years by qualified personnel using techniques approved under the OSHA PSM standards;

C Written operating procedures  are used for training and directing the work of operators;  

C Operators, mechanics, and contractor personnel are qualified and trained in the general hazards in the facility; 

C All site visitors are trained regarding facility emergency procedures;

C A safety work permit system assures that work is done safely and properly;

C A management system is in place to ensure that changes are managed safely;

C Critical equipment, including instruments,  is inspected on a planned, periodic basis to assure proper operating condition;

C Pre-startup safety reviews are done to ensure that conditions for safe operation have been satisfied prior to starting new or modified equipment;

C Incidents, including near-misses, are investigated and recommended enhancements are implemented as part of a continuous improvement effort; 


C Routine audits are conducted to assure that safe practices are being followed; 

C Routine safety meetings are held where managers and hourly participate; and

C Security guards on site 24 hrs/day, 365 days/yr.


This systematic approach to process safety involves employees and strives for continuing imp

rovements in accident reduction.  The training, qualifications, and safety awareness of our operations, maintenance, and emergency response personnel are a key element in reducing and mitigating accidents.


Chemical-Specific Prevention Steps:  Worst-Case Scenarios

Measures that would prevent the worst-case scenarios, a chlorine railcar failure and a dimethylamine railcar failure, include:

C These tanks are pressure vessels which are designed and constructed in accordance with industry pressure vessel standards using industry-standard materials of construction;

C As part of the Mechanical Integrity program, and per DOT requirements (chlorine and dimethylamine railcars ) pressure vessels are periodically inspected and tested;

C The risk of over-pressure is addressed by pressure relief valves installed on the tank cars;

C Access to the facility is restricted through security barriers and trained security personnel, thereby minimizing the risk to the railcars from vehicular damage or sabotage;

C  Fire hazards are controlled through procedures, training, and the hot work permit system (monoethylamine); and

C Continuous observation is required during the unloading of any flammable or toxic gas from railcars.


Chemical-Specific Prevention Steps:  Alternative Release Scenarios

The alternative scenarios selected for anhydrous ammonia, chlorine, dimethylamine, furan, methyl mercaptan, and propylene oxide were a railcar or tank truck unloading line (or flexible hose) connection leaks.  Prevention measures for these scenarios include:

C Railcar and tank truck stops (or wheel chocks) to prevent movement of a railcar or tank truck;

C Signage that indicates railcar unloading and in some areas, visual light indication;

C Careful control of the switching of railcars, including proper training and procedures that prohibit hooking up to a car that is still connected;

C Replacing flexible hose connections and railcar fittings on a frequent basis to ensure hoses are always

 in good condition;

C Frequent inspection of unloading lines to ensure the lines are in good condition; and

C Control of fire hazards through grounding and bonding, procedures, training, and the hot work permit system (dimethylamine). 


The alternative release scenario for ethylene oxide is an overfilled process tank during a transfer from another tank.  Prevention steps for this scenario include:

C Standard operating procedures on tank transfers and periodic reviews (training) of procedures;

C Visible tank level indicator;

C High level indicator and interlock to shut off transfer pump;

C Periodic inspections of the level indicator and alarm system; 

C Radio communication between the control room operator and tank farm operator to minimize the likelihood of tank overfilling.

C Grounding and bonding to control fire hazards related to static electricity.


Five-Year Accident History

There was one incident in the last five years. On July 14, 2001, there was a release of methyl mercaptan vapors/liquid from a railcar.  The methyl mercaptan subsequently ignited creating a fire.  As a result of the fire, sections of flexible hoses on an adjacent chlorine car were damaged, resulting in a release of primarily chlorine vapor.  It is estimated that 26,000 to 27,000 lbs of chlorine was 


released.  Substantially all of the methyl mercaptan (approximately 147,750 lbs) was released in a combusted form during the incident. There were three fatalities and eight additional OSHA recordable injuries as a result of this incident.  In addition, certain residential areas were evacuated as a precautionary measure.  

